<glossary>
<definition id="fs-id1171471258186">
<term>party platform</term>
<meaning id="fs-id1171471092322">the collection of a party’s positions on issues it considers politically important</meaning>
</definition>
<definition id="fs-id1171471303136">
<term>personal politics</term>
<meaning id="fs-id1171471024320">a political style that focuses on building direct relationships with voters rather than on promoting specific issues</meaning>
</definition>
<definition id="fs-id1171473266809">
<term>political machine</term>
<meaning id="fs-id1171470968518">an organization that secures votes for a party’s candidates or supports the party in other ways, usually in exchange for political favors such as a job in government</meaning>
</definition>
<definition id="fs-id1171470993556">
<term>political parties</term>
<meaning id="fs-id1171471020884">organizations made up of groups of people with similar interests that try to directly influence public policy through their members who seek and hold public office</meaning>
</definition>
<definition id="fs-id1171471059857">
<term>third parties</term>
<meaning id="fs-id1171471303733">political parties formed as an alternative to the Republican and Democratic parties, also known as minor parties</meaning>
</definition>
</glossary>
